# BYOA agent setup

BYOA runs an app user's Codex app-server in the developer's Cloudflare account. The user signs in with ChatGPT. The developer does not provide one shared OpenAI API key.

## install

```bash
npx @rishabhsai/byoa deploy
npm install @rishabhsai/byoa
```

No clone is required for an app integration. Repository contributors should read `AGENTS.md`, `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/deploy.md`, `docs/demo.md`, `docs/security.md`, and `docs/launch.md` before changing BYOA itself.

## deploy the runner

Requirements: Cloudflare Workers Paid, Containers, R2, and an authenticated Wrangler session. The deploy command creates the private `byoa-state` bucket. If Cloudflare returns error `10042`, enable R2 in the dashboard and rerun it.

The deploy command creates `BYOA_APP_SECRET` when one is not provided. Save it in the developer backend, which exchanges it for short-lived browser session tokens. Never put it or a Cloudflare credential in browser code.

The default runner limits session issuance to 5 per installation/user per minute and connections to 20 per sandbox per minute. Keep those bindings, add app-level quotas when strict accounting matters, and use the `BYOA_DISABLED=1` Worker secret as the emergency stop.

## add the client

Use `@rishabhsai/byoa` for the protocol client, `@rishabhsai/byoa/server` in the trusted backend, and `@rishabhsai/byoa/react` only if the app uses React.

BYOA is an agent runtime, not a chat abstraction. Use `agent.threads`, `agent.turns`, `agent.workspace`, `agent.models`, `agent.mcp`, and `agent.extensions`. Raw `request()` remains available only for methods admitted by the runner firewall.

Files belong under `/workspace`. The backend sets `workspaceAccess` to `read-only` or `workspace-write`; browser requests cannot broaden it. Use thread `developerInstructions` for app behavior, `AGENTS.md` and skills for durable repo behavior, hooks for lifecycle enforcement, and `outputSchema` for machine-readable output.

Dynamic tools require `experimentalApi: true`. Use `agent.onToolCall()` only for browser-safe tools. Put privileged tools behind the app backend or authenticated MCP; the signed backend tool router is not finished.

The example text and image integration lives in `apps/demo` and is deployed at `https://demo.byoa.lol`. It reads image-generation capability from the signed-in account and renders final `imageGeneration` items. Turnstile is verified server-side before a paid runner session is created.

## do not improvise around blockers

If Containers or R2 are unavailable, stop and enable them. Codex runs locally and only its login file is synced through an R2 mount; `/workspace` remains ephemeral. Do not claim credential durability until a sandbox-replacement test passes in the target account. Do not replace tenant isolation with a shared process or store agent credentials in the workspace.
